      "content": "The civil rights movement in the US can be summarized into several main stages: \n\nAfter World War II, segregation and racism continued, despite the Brown v. Board of Education (1954) ruling desegregating schools. The Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955-1956), led by Martin Luther King Jr., marked the beginning of organized resistance. The March on Washington (1963) and the passage of the Civil Rights Act (1964) and Voting Rights Act (1965) brought significant legislative changes. Tensions continued, with the rise of Black Power and the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. (1968). Ultimately, the movement's efforts led to widespread desegregation, civil rights protections, and increased representation of Black Americans in government and society.",
